# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: hindley-milner-deep
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] A **Hindley–Milner** (**HM**) **type system** is a classical type system for the lambda calculus with parametric polymorphism.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] It is also known as **Damas–Milner** or **Damas–Hindley–Milner**.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] Roger Hindley and later rediscovered by Robin Milner.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] Luis Damas contributed a close formal analysis and proof of the method in his PhD thesis.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] Among HM's more notable properties are its completeness and its ability to infer the most general type of a given program without programmer-supplied type annotations or other hints.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] Algorithm W is an efficient type inference method in practice and has been successfully applied on large code bases, although it has a high theoretical complexity.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] HM is preferably used for functional programming languages.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] It was first implemented as part of the type system of the programming language ML.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] Since then, HM has been extended in various ways, most notably with type class constraints like those in Haskell.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] As a type inference method, Hindley–Milner is able to deduce the types of variables, expressions and functions from programs written in an entirely untyped style.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] Being scope sensitive, it is not limited to deriving the types only from a small portion of source code, but rather from complete programs or modules.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] Being able to cope with parametric types, too, it is core to the type systems of many functional programming languages.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] It was first applied in this manner in the ML programming language.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] The origin is the type inference algorithm for the simply typed lambda calculus that was devised by Haskell Curry and Robert Feys in 1958.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] Roger Hindley extended this work and proved that their algorithm always inferred the most general type.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] In 1978, Robin Milner, independently of Hindley's work, provided an equivalent algorithm, Algorithm W.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] In 1982, Luis Damas finally proved that Milner's algorithm is complete and extended it to support systems with polymorphic references.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] In the simply typed lambda calculus, types T are either atomic type constants or function types of form $T\rightarrow T$ .
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] Contrary to this, the untyped lambda calculus is neutral to typing at all, and many of its functions can be meaningfully applied to all type of arguments.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] which simply returns whatever value it is applied to.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] Less trivial examples include parametric types like lists.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] While polymorphism in general means that operations accept values of more than one type, the polymorphism used here is parametric.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] One finds the notation of *type schemes* in the literature, too, emphasizing the parametric nature of the polymorphism.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] Additionally, constants may be typed with (quantified) type variables.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] Polymorphic types can become monomorphic by consistent substitution of their variables.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] More generally, types are polymorphic when they contain type variables, while types without them are monomorphic.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] Contrary to the type systems used for example in Pascal (1970) or C (1972), which only support monomorphic types, HM is designed with emphasis on parametric polymorphism.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] The successors of the languages mentioned, like C++ (1985), focused on different types of polymorphism, namely subtyping in connection with object-oriented programming and overloading.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] While subtyping is incompatible with HM, a variant of systematic overloading is available in the HM-based type system of Haskell.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] When extending the type inference for the simply-typed lambda calculus towards polymorphism, one has to decide whether assigning a polymorphic type not only as type of an expression, but also as the type of a λ-bound variable is admissible.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] Allowing this gives rise to the polymorphic lambda calculus; however, type inference in this system is not decidable.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] Instead, HM distinguishes variables that are immediately bound to an expression from more general λ-bound variables, calling the former let-bound variables, and allows polymorphic types to be assigned only to these.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] which can be typed with a polymorphic type for 'id'.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] As indicated, the expression syntax is extended to make the let-bound variables explicit, and by restricting the type system to allow only let-bound variable to have polymorphic types, while the parameters in lambda-abstractions must get a monomorphic type, type inference becomes decidable.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] The same description of the deduction system is used throughout, even for the two algorithms, to make the various forms in which the HM method is presented directly comparable.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] The type system can be formally described by syntax rules that fix a language for the expressions, types, etc.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] The presentation here of such a syntax is not too formal, in that it is written down not to study the surface grammar, but rather the depth grammar, and leaves some syntactical details open.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] Building on this, typing rules are used to define how expressions and types are related.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] As before, the form used is a bit liberal.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] The expressions to be typed are exactly those of the lambda calculus extended with a let-expression as shown in the adjacent table.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] Parentheses can be used to disambiguate an expression.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] The application is left-binding and binds stronger than abstraction or the let-in construct.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] Types are syntactically split into two groups, monotypes and polytypes.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] Monotypes always designate a particular type.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] Monotypes $\tau$ are syntactically represented as terms.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] Examples of monotypes include type constants like ${\mathtt {int}}$ or ${\mathtt {string}}$ , and parametric types like ${\mathtt {Map\ (Set\ string)\ int}}$ .
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] The latter types are examples of *applications* of type functions, for example, from the set $\{{\mathtt {Map^{2},\ Set^{1},\ string^{0},\ int^{0}}},\ \rightarrow ^{2}\}$ , where the superscript indicates the number of type parameters.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] The complete set of type functions C is arbitrary in HM, except that it *must* contain at least $\rightarrow ^{2}$ , the type of functions.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] It is often written in infix notation for convenience.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] For example, a function mapping integers to strings has type ${\mathtt {int}}\rightarrow {\mathtt {string}}$ .
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] Again, parentheses can be used to disambiguate a type expression.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] The application binds stronger than the infix arrow, which is right-binding.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] Type variables are admitted as monotypes.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] Monotypes are not to be confused with monomorphic types, which exclude variables and allow only ground terms.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] Two monotypes are equal if they have identical terms.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] A function with polytype $\forall \alpha .\alpha \rightarrow \alpha$ can map *any* value of the same type to itself, and the identity function is a value for this type.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] As another example, $\forall \alpha .({\mathtt {Set}}\ \alpha )\rightarrow {\mathtt {int}}$ is the type of a function mapping all finite sets to integers.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] A function which returns the cardinality of a set would be a value of this type.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] For instance, a type $\forall \alpha .\alpha \rightarrow \forall \alpha .\alpha$ is excluded by the syntax of types.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] Also monotypes are included in the polytypes, thus a type has the general form $\forall \alpha _{1}\dots \forall \alpha _{n}.\tau$ , where $n\geq 0$ and $\tau$ is a monotype.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] Equality of polytypes is up to reordering the quantification and renaming the quantified variables ( $\alpha$ -conversion).
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] Further, quantified variables not occurring in the monotype can be dropped.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] To meaningfully bring together the still disjoint parts (syntax expressions and types) a third part is needed: context.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] In a type $\forall \alpha _{1}\dots \forall \alpha _{n}.\tau$ , the symbol $\forall$ is the quantifier binding the type variables $\alpha _{i}$ in the monotype $\tau$ .
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] The variables $\alpha _{i}$ are called *quantified* and any occurrence of a quantified type variable in $\tau$ is called *bound* and all unbound type variables in $\tau$ are called *free*.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] Additionally to the quantification $\forall$ in polytypes, type variables can also be bound by occurring in the context, but with the inverse effect on the right hand side of the $\vdash$ .
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] Such variables then behave like type constants there.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] Finally, a type variable may legally occur unbound in a typing, in which case they are implicitly all-quantified.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] The presence of both bound and unbound type variables is a bit uncommon in programming languages.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] Often, all type variables are implicitly treated all-quantified.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] For instance, one does not have clauses with free variables in Prolog.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] Likewise in Haskell, where all type variables implicitly occur quantified, i.e. a Haskell type `a -> a` means $\forall \alpha .\alpha \rightarrow \alpha$ here.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] Related and also very uncommon is the binding effect of the right hand side $\sigma$ of the assignments.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] Typically, the mixture of both bound and unbound type variables originate from the use of free variables in an expression.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] The constant function **K** = $\lambda x.\lambda y.x$ provides an example.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] It has the monotype $\alpha \rightarrow \beta \rightarrow \alpha$ .
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] One can force polymorphism by $\mathbf {let} \ k=\lambda x.(\mathbf {let} \ f=\lambda y.x\ \mathbf {in} \ f)\ \mathbf {in} \ k$ .
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] Herein, f has the type $\forall \gamma .\gamma \rightarrow \alpha$ .
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] The free monotype variable $\alpha$ originates from the type of the variable x bound in the surrounding scope. k has the type $\forall \alpha \forall \beta .\alpha \rightarrow \beta \rightarrow \alpha$ .
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] One could imagine the free type variable $\alpha$ in the type of f be bound by the $\forall \alpha$ in the type of k .
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] But such a scoping cannot be expressed in HM.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] Rather, the binding is realized by the context.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] Polymorphism means that one and the same expression can have (perhaps infinitely) many types.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] But in this type system, these types are not completely unrelated, but rather orchestrated by the parametric polymorphism.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] As an example, the identity $\lambda x.x$ can have $\forall \alpha .\alpha \rightarrow \alpha$ as its type as well as ${\texttt {string}}\rightarrow {\texttt {string}}$ or ${\texttt {int}}\rightarrow {\texttt {int}}$ and many others, but not ${\texttt {int}}\rightarrow {\texttt {string}}$ .
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] The most general type for this function is $\forall \alpha .\alpha \rightarrow \alpha$ , while the others are more specific and can be derived from the general one by consistently replacing another type for the *type parameter*, i.e. the quantified variable $\alpha$ .
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] The counter-example fails because the replacement is not consistent.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] The consistent replacement can be made formal by applying a substitution $S=\left\{\ a_{i}\mapsto \tau _{i},\ \dots \ \right\}$ to the term of a type $\tau$ , written $S\tau$ .
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] As the example suggests, substitution is not only strongly related to an order, that expresses that a type is more or less special, but also with the all-quantification which allows the substitution to be applied.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] Formally, in HM, a type $\sigma '$ is more general than $\sigma$ , formally $\sigma '\sqsubseteq \sigma$ , if some quantified variable in $\sigma '$ is consistently substituted such that one gains $\sigma$ as shown in the side bar.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] This order is part of the type definition of the type system.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] In our previous example, applying the substitution $S=\left\{\alpha \mapsto {\texttt {string}}\right\}$ would result in $\forall \alpha .\alpha \rightarrow \alpha \sqsubseteq {\texttt {string}}\rightarrow {\texttt {string}}$ .
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] While substituting a monomorphic (ground) type for a quantified variable is straight forward, substituting a polytype has some pitfalls caused by the presence of free variables.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] Most particularly, unbound variables must not be replaced.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] Additionally, quantifications can only occur top-level.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] Substituting a parametric type, one has to lift its quantifiers.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] The table on the right makes the rule precise.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] Alternatively, consider an equivalent notation for the polytypes without quantifiers in which quantified variables are represented by a different set of symbols.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] In such a notation, the specialization reduces to plain consistent replacement of such variables.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] The relation $\sqsubseteq$ is a partial order and $\forall \alpha .\alpha$ is its smallest element.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] While specialization of a type scheme is one use of the order, it plays a crucial second role in the type system.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] Type inference with polymorphism faces the challenge of summarizing all possible types an expression may have.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] The order guarantees that such a summary exists as the most general type of the expression.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] Contrary to the specialisation rule, this is not part of the definition, but like the implicit all-quantification rather a consequence of the type rules defined next.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] Free type variables in a typing serve as placeholders for possible refinement.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] The binding effect of the environment to free type variables on the right hand side of $\vdash$ that prohibits their substitution in the specialisation rule is again that a replacement has to be consistent and would need to include the whole typing.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] The syntax of HM is carried forward to the syntax of the inference rules that form the body of the formal system, by using the typings as judgments.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] Each of the rules define what conclusion could be drawn from what premises.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] Additionally to the judgments, some extra conditions introduced above might be used as premises, too.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] A proof using the rules is a sequence of judgments such that all premises are listed before a conclusion.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] The examples below show a possible format of proofs.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] From left to right, each line shows the conclusion, the $[{\mathtt {Name}}]$ of the rule applied and the premises, either by referring to an earlier line (number) if the premise is a judgment or by making the predicate explicit.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] The side box shows the deduction rules of the HM type system.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] Their meaning is obvious at the first glance, as they decompose each expression, prove their sub-expressions and finally combine the individual types found in the premises to the type in the conclusion.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] The second group is formed by the remaining two rules $[{\mathtt {Inst}}]$ and $[{\mathtt {Gen}}]$ .
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] They handle specialization and generalization of types.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] While the rule $[{\mathtt {Inst}}]$ should be clear from the section on specialization above, $[{\mathtt {Gen}}]$ complements the former, working in the opposite direction.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] It allows generalization, i.e. to quantify monotype variables not bound in the context.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] The following two examples exercise the rule system in action.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] Since both the expression and the type are given, they are a type-checking use of the rules.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] Not visible immediately, the rule set encodes a regulation under which circumstances a type might be generalized or not by a slightly varying use of mono- and polytypes in the rules $[{\mathtt {Abs}}]$ and $[{\mathtt {Let}}]$ .
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] Remember that $\sigma$ and $\tau$ denote poly- and monotypes respectively.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] The generalisation rule is also worth a closer look.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] Here, the all-quantification implicit in the premise $\Gamma \vdash _{D}e:\sigma$ is simply moved to the right hand side of $\vdash _{D}$ in the conclusion, bound by an explicit universal quantifier.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] This is possible, since $\alpha$ does not occur free in the context.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] Again, while this makes the generalization rule plausible, it is not really a consequence.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] On the contrary, the generalization rule is part of the definition of HM's type system and the implicit all-quantification a consequence.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] Now that the deduction system of HM is at hand, one could present an algorithm and validate it with respect to the rules.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] Alternatively, it might be possible to derive it by taking a closer look on how the rules interact and proof are formed.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] This is done in the remainder of this article focusing on the possible decisions one can make while proving a typing.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] Such a chain could also exist between the conclusion of the proof and the rule for topmost expression.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] All proofs must have the so sketched shape.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] Because the only choice in a proof with respect of rule selection are the $[{\mathtt {Inst}}]$ and $[{\mathtt {Gen}}]$ chains, the form of the proof suggests the question whether it can be made more precise, where these chains might not be needed.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] This is in fact possible and leads to a variant of the rules system with no such rules.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] A contemporary treatment of HM uses a purely syntax-directed rule system due to Clement as an intermediate step.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] In this system, the specialization is located directly after the original $[{\mathtt {Var}}]$ rule and merged into it, while the generalization becomes part of the $[{\mathtt {Let}}]$ rule.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] There the generalization is also determined to always produce the most general type by introducing the function ${\bar {\Gamma }}(\tau )$ , which quantifies all monotype variables not bound in $\Gamma$ .
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] implying, one can derive the principal type for an expression in $\vdash _{S}$ allowing us to generalize the proof in the end.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] Comparing $\vdash _{D}$ and $\vdash _{S}$ , now only monotypes appear in the judgments of all rules.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] Additionally, the shape of any possible proof with the deduction system is now identical to the shape of the expression (both seen as trees).
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] Thus the expression fully determines the shape of the proof.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] In $\vdash _{D}$ the shape would likely be determined with respect to all rules except $[{\mathtt {Inst}}]$ and $[{\mathtt {Gen}}]$ , which allow building arbitrarily long branches (chains) between the other nodes.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] Now that the shape of the proof is known, one is already close to formulating a type inference algorithm.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] Because any proof for a given expression must have the same shape, one can assume the monotypes in the proof's judgements to be undetermined and consider how to determine them.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] Here, the substitution (specialisation) order comes into play.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] The second premise requires that the inferred type is equal to τ of the first premise.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] Now there are two possibly different types, perhaps with open type variables, at hand to compare and to make equal if it is possible.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] If it is, a refinement is found, and if not, a type error is detected again.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] An effective method is known to "make two terms equal" by substitution, Robinson's Unification in combination with the so-called Union-Find algorithm.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] To briefly summarize the union-find algorithm, given the set of all types in a proof, it allows one to group them together into equivalence classes by means of a union procedure and to pick a representative for each such class using a find procedure.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] Emphasizing the word procedure in the sense of side effect, we're clearly leaving the realm of logic in order to prepare an effective algorithm.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] The representative of a ${\mathtt {union}}(a,b)$ is determined such that, if both a and b are type variables then the representative is arbitrarily one of them, but while uniting a variable and a term, the term becomes the representative.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] Now having a sketch of an inference algorithm at hand, a more formal presentation is given in the next section.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] The presentation of Algorithm J is a misuse of the notation of logical rules, since it includes side effects but allows a direct comparison with $\vdash _{S}$ while expressing an efficient implementation at the same time.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] The rules now specify a procedure with parameters $\Gamma ,e$ yielding $\tau$ in the conclusion where the execution of the premises proceeds from left to right.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] The procedure $inst(\sigma )$ specializes the polytype $\sigma$ by copying the term and replacing the bound type variables consistently by new monotype variables.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] ' $newvar$ ' produces a new monotype variable.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] Likely, ${\bar {\Gamma }}(\tau )$ has to copy the type introducing new variables for the quantification to avoid unwanted captures.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] Overall, the algorithm now proceeds by always making the most general choice leaving the specialization to the unification, which by itself produces the most general result.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] As noted above, the final result $\tau$ has to be generalized to ${\bar {\Gamma }}(\tau )$ in the end, to gain the most general type for a given expression.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] Because the procedures used in the algorithm have nearly O(1) cost, the overall cost of the algorithm is close to linear in the size of the expression for which a type is to be inferred.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] This is in strong contrast to many other attempts to derive type inference algorithms, which often came out to be NP-hard, if not undecidable with respect to termination.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] Thus the HM performs as well as the best fully informed type-checking algorithms can.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] Type-checking here means that an algorithm does not have to find a proof, but only to validate a given one.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] Efficiency is slightly reduced because the binding of type variables in the context has to be maintained to allow computation of ${\bar {\Gamma }}(\tau )$ and enable an occurs check to prevent the building of recursive types during ${\mathit {unify}}(\alpha ,\tau )$ .
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] An example of such a case is $\lambda \ x.(x\ x)$ , for which no type can be derived using HM.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] Practically, types are only small terms and do not build up expanding structures.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] Thus, in complexity analysis, one can treat comparing them as a constant, retaining O(1) costs.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] In the previous section, while sketching the algorithm its proof was hinted at with metalogical argumentation.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] While this leads to an efficient algorithm J, it is not clear whether the algorithm properly reflects the deduction systems D or S which serve as a semantic base line.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] The most critical point in the above argumentation is the refinement of monotype variables bound by the context.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] For instance, the algorithm boldly changes the context while inferring e.g. $\lambda f.(f\ 1)$ , because the monotype variable added to the context for the parameter f later needs to be refined to $int\rightarrow \beta$ when handling application.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] The problem is that the deduction rules do not allow such a refinement.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] Arguing that the refined type could have been added earlier instead of the monotype variable is an expedient at best.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] The key to reaching a formally satisfying argument is to properly include the context within the refinement.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] Formally, typing is compatible with substitution of free type variables.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] To refine the free variables thus means to refine the whole typing.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] From there, a proof of algorithm J leads to algorithm W, which only makes the side effects imposed by the procedure ${\textit {union}}$ explicit by expressing its serial composition by means of the substitutions $S_{i}$ .
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] The presentation of algorithm W in the sidebar still makes use of side effects in the operations set in italic, but these are now limited to generating fresh symbols.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] The form of judgement is $\Gamma \vdash e:\tau ,S$ , denoting a function with a context and expression as parameter producing a monotype together with a substitution. ${\textsf {mgu}}$ is a side-effect free version of ${\textit {union}}$ producing a substitution which is the most general unifier.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] While algorithm W is normally considered to be *the* HM algorithm and is often directly presented after the rule system in literature, its purpose is described by Milner on P.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] As it stands, W is hardly an efficient algorithm; substitutions are applied too often.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] It was formulated to aid the proof of soundness.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] We now present a simpler algorithm J which simulates W in a precise sense.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] While he considered W more complicated and less efficient, he presented it in his publication before J.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] It has its merits when side effects are unavailable or unwanted.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] W is also needed to prove completeness, which is factored by him into the soundness proof.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] Before formulating the proof obligations, a deviation between the rules systems D and S and the algorithms presented needs to be emphasized.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] While the development above sort of misused the monotypes as "open" proof variables, the possibility that proper monotype variables might be harmed was sidestepped by introducing fresh variables and hoping for the best.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] But there's a catch: One of the promises made was that these fresh variables would be "kept in mind" as such.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] This promise is not fulfilled by the algorithm.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] This omission can easily be fixed by more carefully distinguishing proof variables and monotype variables.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] The authors were well aware of the problem but decided not to fix it.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] One might assume a pragmatic reason behind this.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] While more properly implementing the type inference would have enabled the algorithm to deal with abstract monotypes, they were not needed for the intended application where none of the items in a preexisting context have free variables.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] In this light, the unneeded complication was dropped in favor of a simpler algorithm.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] The remaining downside is that the proof of the algorithm with respect to the rule system is less general and can only be made for contexts with $free(\Gamma )=\emptyset$ as a side condition.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] The side condition in the completeness obligation addresses how the deduction may give many types, while the algorithm always produces one.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] At the same time, the side condition demands that the type inferred is actually the most general.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] To properly prove the obligations one needs to strengthen them first to allow activating the substitution lemma threading the substitution S through $\vdash _{S}$ and $\vdash _{W}$ .
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] From there, the proofs are by induction over the expression.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] Another proof obligation is the substitution lemma itself, i.e. the substitution of the typing, which finally establishes the all-quantification.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] The later cannot formally be proven, since no such syntax is at hand.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] To make programming practical recursive functions are needed.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] A central property of the lambda calculus is that recursive definitions are not directly available, but can instead be expressed with a fixed point combinator.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] However, the fixpoint combinator cannot be formulated in a typed version of the lambda calculus without having a disastrous effect on the system as outlined below.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] The original paper shows recursion can be realized by a combinator ${\mathit {fix}}:\forall \alpha .(\alpha \rightarrow \alpha )\rightarrow \alpha$ .
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] basically merging $[{\mathtt {Abs}}]$ and $[{\mathtt {Let}}]$ while including the recursively defined variables in monotype positions where they occur to the left of the ${\mathtt {in}}$ but as polytypes to the right of it.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] While the above is straightforward it does come at a price.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] Type theory connects lambda calculus with computation and logic.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] Overloading means that different functions can be defined and used with the same name.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] Most programming languages at least provide overloading with the built-in arithmetic operations (+, <, etc.), to allow the programmer to write arithmetic expressions in the same form, even for different numerical types like `int` or `real`.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] Because a mixture of these different types within the same expression also demands for implicit conversion, overloading especially for these operations is often built into the programming language itself.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] In some languages, this feature is generalized and made available to the user, e.g. in C++.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] While ad hoc overloading has been avoided in functional programming for the computation costs both in type checking and inference, a means to systematise overloading has been introduced that resembles both in form and naming to object oriented programming, but works one level upwards.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] "Instances" in this systematic are not objects (i.e. on value level), but rather types.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] Herein, the type `a` is not only polymorphic, but also restricted to be an instance of some type class `Ord`, that provides the order predicates `<` and `>=` used in the functions body.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] The proper implementations of these predicates are then passed to quicksorts as additional parameters, as soon as quicksort is used on more concrete types providing a single implementation of the overloaded function quickSort.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] Because the "classes" only allow a single type as their argument, the resulting type system can still provide inference.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] Additionally, the type classes can then be equipped with some kind of overloading order allowing one to arrange the classes as a lattice.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] Parametric polymorphism implies that types themselves are passed as parameters as if they were proper values.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] Passed as arguments to a proper functions, but also into "type functions" as in the "parametric" type constants, leads to the question how to more properly type types themselves.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] Higher-order types are used to create an even more expressive type system.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] Unification is no longer decidable in the presence of meta types, rendering type inference impossible in this extend of generality.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] Additionally, assuming a type of all types that includes itself as type leads into a paradox, as in the set of all sets, so one must proceed in steps of levels of abstraction.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] Research in second order lambda calculus, one step upwards, showed that type inference is undecidable in this generality.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] Haskell introduces one higher level named kind.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] Language extensions are available which extend kinds to emulate features of a dependent type system.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] Attempts to combine subtyping and type inference have caused quite some frustration.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] However, because type variables are no longer unified eagerly in this approach, it tends to generate large and unwieldy typing schemes containing many useless type variables and constraints, making them hard to read and understand.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] Therefore, considerable effort was put into simplifying such typing schemes and their constraints, using techniques similar to those of nondeterministic finite automaton (NFA) simplification (useful in the presence of inferred recursive types).
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] More recently, Dolan and Mycroft formalized the relationship between typing scheme simplification and NFA simplification and showed that an algebraic take on the formalization of subtyping allowed generating compact principal typing schemes for an ML-like language (called MLsub).
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] Notably, their proposed typing scheme used a restricted form of union and intersection types instead of explicit constraints.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] Parreaux later claimed that this algebraic formulation was equivalent to a relatively simple algorithm resembling Algorithm W, and that the use of union and intersection types was not essential.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] On the other hand, type inference has proven more difficult in the context of object-oriented programming languages, because object methods tend to require first-class polymorphism in the style of System F (where type inference is undecidable) and because of features like F-bounded polymorphism.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] Consequently, type systems with subtyping enabling object-oriented programming, such as Cardelli's system $F_{<:}$ , do not support HM-style type inference.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] Row polymorphism can be used as an alternative to subtyping for supporting language features like structural records.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/hindley-milner-type-system] While this style of polymorphism is less flexible than subtyping in some ways, notably requiring more polymorphism than strictly necessary to cope with the lack of directionality in type constraints, it has the advantage that it can be integrated with the standard HM algorithms quite easily.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/ml-programming-language] ML started development by Robin Milner upon his arrival at University of Edinburgh in 1973 with the help of research assistants Lockwood Morris and Malcolm Newey, both postdocs from Stanford who were hired by Milner.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/ml-programming-language] Michael Gordon, Christopher Wadsworth, and other graduate students joined in research by 1975.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/ml-programming-language] Historically, ML was conceived to develop proof tactics in the LCF theorem prover and succeed the previous iteration *Stanford LCF*, trying to solve issues regarding space utilization and proof extensibility.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/ml-programming-language] ML acted as both a metalanguage (hence the name) and command (REPL) language for the LCF system*.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/ml-programming-language] PPLAMBDA*, a language that was conceptually a combination of the first-order predicate calculus and the simply typed polymorphic lambda calculus, was the underlying language that theorem statements were more directly constructed in.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/ml-programming-language] As ML was being developed, Milner wrote the paper *A theory of type polymorphism in programming* in 1978, which laid out the ideas of what it meant for a program to be well-typed in the context of a polymorphic (generic) type system.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/ml-programming-language] He used ML as the case-study application of the theorems developed and noted the theoretical challenges that arose with development that had yet to have been solved.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/ml-programming-language] The design of the first version of ML was finalized, and subsequently documented in the 1979 book *Edinburgh LCF* by Milner along with Gordon and Wadsworth.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/ml-programming-language] After *Edinburgh LCF* was established with the publication of the same name, interest in the language grew and several implementations, all with slight alterations in design and features, were underway by several parties.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/ml-programming-language] Luca Cardelli created *Cardelli ML*, or *VAX ML*, which eventually grew into a standalone dialect fit for general-purpose computing, specified with the paper *ML under Unix*.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/ml-programming-language] Gérard Huet at Inria began porting the source code from Stanford Lisp to various other dialects of Lisp in "Project Formel".
[src:hindley-milner-deep/ml-programming-language] The port to Franz Lisp was further developed by Larry Paulson, whose version eventually was coined *Cambridge LCF*.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/ml-programming-language] This version of the LCF was subsequently updated to use an early version of Standard ML, and has been uploaded to GitHub.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/ml-programming-language] Concerns with the splintering of both design and implementation leading to duplicated work was raised in this meeting.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/ml-programming-language] Although Milner seemed open to the spirit of experimentation in the meeting, further discussions and meetings were had between Bernard Sufrin and Milner, where Sufrin urged Milner to unify the design of ML.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/ml-programming-language] These correspondences were later referenced in the second draft of Milner's proposal for Standard ML.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/ml-programming-language] The most notable inspiration of the syntax of ML can be traced to ISWIM, a language that was described as "lambda calculus with syntactic sugar".
[src:hindley-milner-deep/ml-programming-language] ML was designed with a strong static type system that allowed the user to define abstract types with parametric polymorphism and was checked at compile-time.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/ml-programming-language] It also had automatic type inference, which afforded ML the ease-of-use of dynamic languages of the time such as Lisp or POP-2 by foregoing the need for explicit type annotations.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/ml-programming-language] The following examples are very closely derived from *Edinburgh LCF*, showing a rough overview of the syntax and features of ML.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/ml-programming-language] The `#` character at the start of a line denotes user input, and lines without it are system responses showing the value and its inferred type.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/ml-programming-language] Note that this section is not meant to act as a comprehensive set of language features that ML contains, rather a subset to give a sense for the language.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/ml-programming-language] Refer to *Edinburgh LCF* for a more rigorous definition.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/ml-programming-language] Expressions are evaluated by typing them followed by `;;` and a return character.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/ml-programming-language] The identifier `it` holds the result of the last-evaluated expression.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/ml-programming-language] Function application is higher precedent than mathematical operators, so `f 3 + 4` means `(f 3) + 4`.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/ml-programming-language] Functions defined with multiple parameters are curried, so passing one parameter into the function will return a function that will accept the second, and so on.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/ml-programming-language] Recursive functions require `letrec` so the function name is in scope within its body.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/ml-programming-language] `hd` and `tl` are built-in functions that return the head and tail; `.` is cons (prepend); `@` is append.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/ml-programming-language] Mutable variables are declared with `letref` and updated with `:=`.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/ml-programming-language] Tokens are ML's string type, delimited by `; double backticks create token lists.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/ml-programming-language] Abstract types are declared with `abstype`, which creates a new type and defines the functions that work with it, while keeping the internal structure (the concrete type it's built from) hidden.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/ml-programming-language] Abstract recursive types are declared with `absrectype`, which allows the type to be used in its own definition.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/ml-programming-language] There is a similar keyword `lettype`, which is used for more basic type aliasing.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/ml-programming-language] Inside the operation definitions (the `with` block), the type's name can be prepended with `abs` to box values in the type and `rep` to unbox values.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/ml-programming-language] The characters `+` and `#` in type definitions signify sum types (tagged unions) and product types (tuples), respectively, with `#` having a higher precedence.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/ml-programming-language] ML on LCF provided several helper functions used in the example above.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/ml-programming-language] Operating on sum types `+`, the functions `inl` and `inr` inject values into the left or right side of a sum type.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/ml-programming-language] `outl` extracts from left injections (fails if given a right injection), and `outr` extracts from right injections (fails if given a left injection).
[src:hindley-milner-deep/ml-programming-language] For product types `#`, the extraction functions are `fst` and `snd`, which extract the first and second components of a pair.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/ml-programming-language] Product types are constructed using the comma infix operator.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/ml-programming-language] In the tree example above, `comptree` takes a single parameter that is a pair pattern `(y, t1, t2)`, which destructures the pair into its three components.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/ocaml] The OCaml toolchain includes an interactive top-level interpreter, a bytecode compiler, an optimizing native code compiler, a reversible debugger, and a package manager (OPAM) together with a composable build system for OCaml (Dune).
[src:hindley-milner-deep/ocaml] OCaml was developed first in the context of automated theorem proving, and is used in static analysis and formal methods software.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/ocaml] Beyond these areas, it has found use in systems programming, web development, and specific financial utilities, among other application domains.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/ocaml] The acronym *CAML* originally stood for *Categorical Abstract Machine Language*, but OCaml omits this abstract machine.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/ocaml] OCaml is a free and open-source software project managed and principally maintained by the French Institute for Research in Computer Science and Automation (Inria).
[src:hindley-milner-deep/ocaml] In the early 2000s, elements from OCaml were adopted by many languages, notably F# and Scala.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/ocaml] ML-derived languages are best known for their static type systems and type-inferring compilers.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/ocaml] OCaml unifies functional, imperative, and object-oriented programming under an ML-like type system.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/ocaml] Thus, programmers need not be highly familiar with the pure functional language paradigm to use OCaml.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/ocaml] By requiring the programmer to work within the constraints of its static type system, OCaml eliminates many of the type-related runtime problems associated with dynamically typed languages.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/ocaml] Also, OCaml's type-inferring compiler greatly reduces the need for the manual type annotations that are required in most statically typed languages.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/ocaml] For example, the data types of variables and the signatures of functions usually need not be declared explicitly, as they do in languages like Java and C#, because they can be inferred from the operators and other functions that are applied to the variables and other values in the code.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/ocaml] Effective use of OCaml's type system can require some sophistication on the part of a programmer, but this discipline is rewarded with reliable, high-performance software.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/ocaml] OCaml is perhaps most distinguished from other languages with origins in academia by its emphasis on performance.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/ocaml] These are rare enough that avoiding them is quite possible in practice.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/ocaml] Aside from type-checking overhead, functional programming languages are, in general, challenging to compile to efficient machine language code, due to issues such as the funarg problem.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/ocaml] Xavier Leroy has stated that "OCaml delivers at least 50% of the performance of a decent C compiler", although a direct comparison is impossible.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/ocaml] Some functions in the OCaml standard library are implemented with faster algorithms than equivalent functions in the standard libraries of other languages.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/ocaml] Between the 1970s and 1980s, Robin Milner, a British computer scientist and Turing Award winner, worked at the University of Edinburgh's Laboratory for Foundations of Computer Science.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/ocaml] Milner and others were working on theorem provers, which were historically developed in languages such as Lisp.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/ocaml] Milner repeatedly ran into the issue that the theorem provers would attempt to claim a proof was valid by putting non-proofs together.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/ocaml] As a result, he went on to develop the meta language for his Logic for Computable Functions, a language that would only allow the writer to construct valid proofs with its polymorphic type system.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/ocaml] ML was turned into a compiler to simplify using LCF on different machines, and, by the 1980s, was turned into a complete system of its own.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/ocaml] ML would eventually serve as a basis for the creation of OCaml.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/ocaml] In the early 1980s, there were some developments that prompted INRIA's Formel team to become interested in the ML language.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/ocaml] Luca Cardelli, a research professor at University of Oxford, used his *functional abstract machine* to develop a faster implementation of ML, and Robin Milner proposed a new definition of ML to avoid divergence between various implementations.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/ocaml] Simultaneously, Pierre-Louis Curien, a senior researcher at Paris Diderot University, developed a calculus of categorical combinators and linked it to lambda calculus, which led to the definition of the *categorical abstract machine* (CAM).
[src:hindley-milner-deep/ocaml] Guy Cousineau, a researcher at Paris Diderot University, recognized that this could be applied as a compiling method for ML.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/ocaml] Caml was designed and developed first by INRIA's Formel team headed by Gérard Huet.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/ocaml] The first implementation of Caml was created in 1987 and was further developed until 1992.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/ocaml] Though it was spearheaded by Ascánder Suárez, Pierre Weis and Michel Mauny carried on with development after he left in 1988.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/ocaml] Guy Cousineau is quoted recalling that his experience with programming language implementation was initially very limited, and that there were multiple inadequacies for which he is responsible.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/ocaml] Between 1990 and 1991, Xavier Leroy designed a new implementation of Caml based on a bytecode interpreter written in C.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/ocaml] In addition to this, Damien Doligez wrote a memory management system, also known as a sequential garbage collector, for this implementation.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/ocaml] This new implementation, known as Caml Light, replaced the old Caml implementation and ran on small desktop machines.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/ocaml] In the following years, libraries such as Michel Mauny's syntax manipulation tools appeared and helped promote the use of Caml in educational and research teams.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/ocaml] In 1995, Xavier Leroy released Caml Special Light, which was an improved version of Caml.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/ocaml] An optimizing native-code compiler was added to the bytecode compiler, which greatly increased performance to comparable levels with mainstream languages such as C++.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/ocaml] Also, Leroy designed a high-level module system inspired by the module system of Standard ML which provided powerful facilities for abstraction and parameterization and made larger-scale programs easier to build.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/ocaml] Didier Rémy and Jérôme Vouillon designed an expressive type system for objects and classes, which was integrated within Caml Special Light.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/ocaml] This led to the emergence of the Objective Caml language, first released in 1996 and subsequently renamed to OCaml in 2011.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/ocaml] This object system notably supported many prevalent object-oriented idioms in a statically type-safe way, while those same idioms caused unsoundness or required runtime checks in languages such as C++ or Java.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/ocaml] In 2000, Jacques Garrigue extended Objective Caml with multiple new features such as polymorphic methods, variants, and labeled and optional arguments.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/ocaml] Language improvements have been incrementally added for the last two decades to support the growing commercial and academic codebases in OCaml.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/ocaml] The OCaml 4.0 release in 2012 added Generalized Algebraic Data Types (GADTs) and first-class modules to increase the flexibility of the language.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/ocaml] The OCaml 5.0.0 release in 2022 is a complete rewrite of the language runtime, removing the global GC lock and adding effect handlers via delimited continuations.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/ocaml] These changes enable support for shared-memory parallelism and color-blind concurrency, respectively.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/ocaml] OCaml's development continued within the Cristal team at INRIA until 2005, when it was succeeded by the Gallium team.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/ocaml] Subsequently, Gallium was succeeded by the Cambium team in 2019.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/ocaml] As of 2023, there are 23 core developers of the compiler distribution from a variety of organizations and 41 developers for the broader OCaml tooling and packaging ecosystem.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/ocaml] In 2023, the OCaml compiler was recognised with ACM SIGPLAN's Programming Languages Software Award.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/ocaml] OCaml features a static type system, type inference, parametric polymorphism, tail recursion, pattern matching, first class lexical closures, functors (parametric modules), exception handling, effect handling, and incremental generational automatic garbage collection.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/ocaml] OCaml is notable for extending ML-style type inference to an object system in a general-purpose language.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/ocaml] This permits structural subtyping, where object types are compatible if their method signatures are compatible, regardless of their declared inheritance (an unusual feature in statically typed languages).
[src:hindley-milner-deep/ocaml] A foreign function interface for linking to C primitives is provided, including language support for efficient numerical arrays in formats compatible with both C and Fortran.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/ocaml] OCaml also supports creating libraries of OCaml functions that can be linked to a *main* program in C, so that an OCaml library can be distributed to C programmers who have no knowledge or installation of OCaml.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/ocaml] Although OCaml does not have a macro system as an indivisible part of the language (metaprogramming), i.e. built-in support for preprocessing, the OCaml platform does officially support a library for writing such preprocessors.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/ocaml] These can be of two types: one that works at the source code level (as in C), and one that works on the Abstract Syntax Tree level.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/ocaml] The latter, which is called PPX, acronym for Pre-Processor eXtension, is the recommended one.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/ocaml] The native code compiler is available for many platforms, including Unix, Microsoft Windows, and Apple macOS.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/ocaml] The bytecode compiler supports operation on any 32- or 64-bit architecture when native code generation is not available, requiring only a C compiler.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/ocaml] OCaml bytecode and native code programs can be written in a multithreaded style, with preemptive context switching.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/ocaml] OCaml threads in the same domain execute by time sharing only.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/ocaml] However, an OCaml program can contain several domains.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/ocaml] Snippets of OCaml code are most easily studied by entering them into the *top-level REPL*.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/ocaml] This is an interactive OCaml session that prints the inferred types of resulting or defined expressions.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/ocaml] Code can then be entered at the "#" prompt.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/ocaml] OCaml infers the type of the expression to be "int" (a machine-precision integer) and gives the result "7".
[src:hindley-milner-deep/ocaml] The first argument to ocamlc, "hello.ml", specifies the source file to compile and the "-o hello" flag specifies the output file.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/ocaml] The `option` type constructor in OCaml, similar to the `Maybe` type in Haskell, augments a given data type to either return `Some` value of the given data type, or to return `None`.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/ocaml] This is used to express that a value might or might not be present.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/ocaml] Lists are one of the fundamental datatypes in OCaml.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/ocaml] The following code example defines a recursive function *sum* that accepts one argument, *integers*, which is supposed to be a list of integers.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/ocaml] Note the keyword `rec` which denotes that the function is recursive.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/ocaml] The function recursively iterates over the given list of integers and provides a sum of the elements.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/ocaml] The *match* statement has similarities to C's switch element, though it is far more general.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/ocaml] Another way is to use standard fold function that works with lists.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/ocaml] OCaml lends itself to concisely expressing recursive algorithms.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/ocaml] The following code example implements an algorithm similar to quicksort that sorts a list in increasing order.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/ocaml] Or using partial application of the >= operator.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/ocaml] The following program calculates the smallest number of people in a room for whom the probability of completely unique birthdays is less than 50% (the birthday problem, where for 1 person the probability is 365/365 (or 100%), for 2 it is 364/365, for 3 it is 364/365 × 363/365, etc.) (answer = 23).
[src:hindley-milner-deep/ocaml] The following code defines a Church encoding of natural numbers, with successor (succ) and addition (add).
[src:hindley-milner-deep/ocaml] A Church numeral `n` is a higher-order function that accepts a function `f` and a value `x` and applies `f` to `x` exactly `n` times.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/ocaml] To convert a Church numeral from a functional value to a string, we pass it a function that prepends the string `"S"` to its input and the constant string `"0"`.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/ocaml] The given example outputs the Church numeral for five as “SSSSS0”.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/ocaml] A variety of libraries are directly accessible from OCaml.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/ocaml] For example, OCaml has a built-in library for arbitrary-precision arithmetic.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/ocaml] As the factorial function grows very rapidly, it quickly overflows machine-precision numbers (typically 32- or 64-bits).
[src:hindley-milner-deep/ocaml] Thus, factorial is a suitable candidate for arbitrary-precision arithmetic.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/ocaml] The LablGL bindings to OpenGL are required.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/ocaml] Far more sophisticated, high-performance 2D and 3D graphical programs can be developed in OCaml.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/ocaml] Thanks to the use of OpenGL and OCaml, the resulting programs can be cross-platform, compiling without any changes on many major platforms.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/ocaml] The following code calculates the Fibonacci sequence of a number *n* inputted.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/ocaml] It uses tail recursion and pattern matching.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/ocaml] Functions may take functions as input and return functions as result.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/ocaml] For example, applying *twice* to a function *f* yields a function that applies *f* two times to its argument.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/ocaml] The function *twice* uses a type variable*'a* to indicate that it can be applied to any function *f* mapping from a type*'a* to itself, rather than only to *int->int* functions.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/ocaml] In particular, *twice* can even be applied to itself.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/ocaml] MetaOCaml is a multi-stage programming extension of OCaml enabling incremental compiling of new machine code during runtime.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/ocaml] Under some circumstances, significant speedups are possible using multistage programming, because more detailed information about the data to process is available at runtime than at the regular compile time, so the incremental compiler can optimize away many cases of condition checking, etc.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/ocaml] The new function is automatically compiled.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/ocaml] At least several dozen companies use OCaml to some degree.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/ocaml] In the context of academic teaching and research, OCaml has a remarkable presence in computer science teaching programmes, both in universities and colleges.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/ocaml] A list of educational resources and these teaching programmes can be found at ocaml.org.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/robin-milner] Milner was born in Yealmpton, near Plymouth, England into a military family.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/robin-milner] He gained a King's Scholarship to Eton College in 1947, and was awarded the Tomline Prize (the highest prize in Mathematics at Eton) in 1952.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/robin-milner] Subsequently, he served in the Royal Engineers, attaining the rank of Second Lieutenant.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/robin-milner] He then enrolled at King's College, Cambridge, graduating in 1957.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/robin-milner] He returned to Cambridge as the head of the Computer Laboratory in 1995 from which he eventually stepped down, although he was still at the laboratory.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/robin-milner] From 2009, Milner was a Scottish Informatics & Computer Science Alliance Advanced Research Fellow and held (part-time) the chair of computer science at the University of Edinburgh.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/robin-milner] Milner died of a heart attack on 20 March 2010 in Cambridge.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/robin-milner] His wife, Lucy, died shortly before he did.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/robin-milner] Milner is generally regarded as having made three major contributions to computer science.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/robin-milner] He developed Logic for Computable Functions (LCF), one of the first tools for automated theorem proving.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/robin-milner] The language he developed for LCF, ML, was the first language with polymorphic type inference, type-safe exception handling, and an automatically inferred type system, using algorithm W.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/robin-milner] Milner also developed two theoretical frameworks for analyzing concurrent systems, the calculus of communicating systems (CCS), and its successor, the π-calculus.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/robin-milner] At the time of his death, he was working on bigraphs, a formalism for ubiquitous computing subsuming CCS and the π-calculus.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/robin-milner] He is also credited for rediscovering the Hindley–Milner type system.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/robin-milner] He was made a Fellow of the Royal Society and a Distinguished Fellow of the British Computer Society in 1988.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/robin-milner] Milner received the ACM Turing Award in 1991.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/robin-milner] In 1994 he was inducted as a Fellow of the ACM.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/robin-milner] In 2004, the Royal Society of Edinburgh awarded Milner with a Royal Medal for his "bringing about public benefits on a global scale".
[src:hindley-milner-deep/robin-milner] The Royal Society Milner Award and the ACM SIGPLAN Robin Milner Young Researcher Award are both named after him.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/standard-ml] Standard ML is a modern dialect of ML, the language used in the Logic for Computable Functions (LCF) theorem-proving project.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/standard-ml] It is distinctive among widely used languages in that it has a formal specification, given as typing rules and operational semantics in *The Definition of Standard ML*, originally released in 1990, with a second and final revision being released in 1997.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/standard-ml] Standard ML is a functional programming language with some impure features.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/standard-ml] Programs written in Standard ML consist of expressions in contrast to statements or commands, although some expressions of type unit are only evaluated for their side-effects.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/standard-ml] Like all functional languages, a key feature of Standard ML is the function, which is used for abstraction.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/standard-ml] An SML compiler must infer the static type `val factorial : int -> int` without user-supplied type annotations.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/standard-ml] It has to deduce that `n` is only used with integer expressions, and must therefore itself be an integer, and that all terminal expressions are integer expressions.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/standard-ml] Here, the keyword `val` introduces a binding of an identifier to a value, `fn` introduces an anonymous function, and `rec` allows the definition to be self-referential.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/standard-ml] The encapsulation of an invariant-preserving tail-recursive tight loop with one or more accumulator parameters within an invariant-free outer function, as seen here, is a common idiom in Standard ML.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/standard-ml] A type synonym is defined with the keyword `type`.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/standard-ml] Here is a type synonym for points on a plane, and functions computing the distances between two points, and the area of a triangle with the given corners as per Heron's formula.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/standard-ml] (These definitions will be used in subsequent examples).
[src:hindley-milner-deep/standard-ml] Standard ML provides strong support for algebraic datatypes (ADT).
[src:hindley-milner-deep/standard-ml] A data type can be thought of as a disjoint union of tuples (or a "sum of products").
[src:hindley-milner-deep/standard-ml] They are easy to define and easy to use, largely because of pattern matching, and most Standard ML implementations' pattern-exhaustiveness checking and pattern redundancy checking.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/standard-ml] In object-oriented programming languages, a disjoint union can be expressed as class hierarchies.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/standard-ml] However, in contrast to class hierarchies, ADTs are closed.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/standard-ml] Thus, the extensibility of ADTs is orthogonal to the extensibility of class hierarchies.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/standard-ml] Class hierarchies can be extended with new subclasses which implement the same interface, while the functions of ADTs can be extended for the fixed set of constructors.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/standard-ml] Note that a type synonym cannot be recursive; datatypes are necessary to define recursive constructors.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/standard-ml] Patterns are matched in the order in which they are defined.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/standard-ml] C programmers can use tagged unions, dispatching on tag values, to do what ML does with datatypes and pattern matching.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/standard-ml] Nevertheless, while a C program decorated with appropriate checks will, in a sense, be as robust as the corresponding ML program, those checks will of necessity be dynamic; ML's static checks provide strong guarantees about the correctness of the program at compile time.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/standard-ml] Pattern-exhaustiveness checking will make sure that each constructor of the datatype is matched by at least one pattern.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/standard-ml] There is no pattern for the `Triangle` case in the `center` function.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/standard-ml] The compiler will issue a warning that the case expression is not exhaustive, and if a `Triangle` is passed to this function at runtime, `exception Match` will be raised.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/standard-ml] Any value that would match the pattern in the second clause would also match the pattern in the first clause, so the second clause is unreachable.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/standard-ml] Therefore, this definition as a whole exhibits redundancy, and causes a compile-time warning.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/standard-ml] If control gets past the first pattern (`Circle`), we know the shape must be either a `Square` or a `Triangle`.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/standard-ml] In either of those cases, we know the shape has corners, so we can return `true` without discerning the actual shape.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/standard-ml] Exceptions are raised with the keyword `raise` and handled with the pattern matching `handle` construct.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/standard-ml] The exception system can implement non-local exit; this optimization technique is suitable for functions like the following.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/standard-ml] When `exception Zero` is raised, control leaves the function `List.foldl` altogether.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/standard-ml] Consider the alternative: the value 0 would be returned, it would be multiplied by the next integer in the list, the resulting value (inevitably 0) would be returned, and so on.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/standard-ml] The raising of the exception allows control to skip over the entire chain of frames and avoid the associated computation.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/standard-ml] Note the use of the underscore (`_`) as a wildcard pattern.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/standard-ml] The same optimization can be obtained with a tail call.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/standard-ml] Standard ML's advanced module system allows programs to be decomposed into hierarchically organized *structures* of logically related type and value definitions.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/standard-ml] Modules provide not only namespace control but also abstraction, in the sense that they allow the definition of abstract data types.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/standard-ml] Three main syntactic constructs comprise the module system: signatures, structures and functors.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/standard-ml] A *signature* is an interface, usually thought of as a type for a structure; it specifies the names of all entities provided by the structure, the arity of each type component, the type of each value component, and the signature of each substructure.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/standard-ml] The definitions of type components are optional; type components whose definitions are hidden are *abstract types*.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/standard-ml] This signature describes a module that provides a polymorphic type `'a queue`, `exception QueueError`, and values that define basic operations on queues.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/standard-ml] A *structure* is a module; it consists of a collection of types, exceptions, values and structures (called *substructures*) packaged together into a logical unit.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/standard-ml] This definition declares that `structure TwoListQueue` implements `signature QUEUE`.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/standard-ml] Furthermore, the *opaque ascription* denoted by `:>` states that any types which are not defined in the signature (i.e.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/standard-ml] `type 'a queue`) should be abstract, meaning that the definition of a queue as a pair of lists is not visible outside the module.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/standard-ml] The structure implements all of the definitions in the signature.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/standard-ml] A *functor* is a function from structures to structures; that is, a functor accepts one or more arguments, which are usually structures of a given signature, and produces a structure as its result.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/standard-ml] Functors are used to implement generic data structures and algorithms.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/standard-ml] One popular algorithm for breadth-first search of trees makes use of queues.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/standard-ml] Within `functor BFS`, the representation of the queue is not visible.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/standard-ml] More concretely, there is no way to select the first list in the two-list queue, if that is indeed the representation being used.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/standard-ml] This data abstraction mechanism makes the breadth-first search truly agnostic to the queue's implementation.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/standard-ml] This is in general desirable; in this case, the queue structure can safely maintain any logical invariants on which its correctness depends behind the bulletproof wall of abstraction.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/standard-ml] Snippets of SML code are most easily studied by entering them into an interactive top-level.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/standard-ml] Here, the classic mergesort algorithm is implemented in three functions: split, merge and mergesort.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/standard-ml] Also note the absence of types, with the exception of the syntax `op ::` and `[]` which signify lists.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/standard-ml] This code will sort lists of any type, so long as a consistent ordering function `cmp` is defined.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/standard-ml] Using Hindley–Milner type inference, the types of all variables can be inferred, even complicated types such as that of the function `cmp`.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/standard-ml] Merge uses a local function loop for efficiency.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/standard-ml] The inner `loop` is defined in terms of cases: when both lists are non-empty (`x :: xs`) and when one list is empty (`[]`).
[src:hindley-milner-deep/standard-ml] This function merges two sorted lists into one sorted list.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/standard-ml] Note how the accumulator `acc` is built backwards, then reversed before being returned.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/standard-ml] This is a common technique, since `'a list` is represented as a linked list; this technique requires more clock time, but the asymptotics are not worse.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/standard-ml] `fun part` is a closure that consumes an order operator `op <<`.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/standard-ml] The `IntInf` module provides arbitrary-precision integer arithmetic.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/standard-ml] Moreover, integer literals may be used as arbitrary-precision integers without the programmer having to do anything.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/standard-ml] Curried functions have many applications, such as eliminating redundant code.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/standard-ml] For example, a module may require functions of type `a -> b`, but it is more convenient to write functions of type `a * c -> b` where there is a fixed relationship between the objects of type `a` and `c`.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/standard-ml] A function of type `c -> (a * c -> b) -> a -> b` can factor out this commonality.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/standard-ml] This is an example of the adapter pattern.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/standard-ml] The type of `fun d` indicates that it maps a "float" onto a function with the type `(real -> real) -> real -> real`.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/standard-ml] This allows us to partially apply arguments, known as currying.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/standard-ml] In this case, function `d` can be specialised by partially applying it with the argument `delta`.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/standard-ml] A good choice for `delta` when using this algorithm is the cube root of the machine epsilon.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/standard-ml] The inferred type indicates that `d'` expects a function with the type `real -> real` as its first argument.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/standard-ml] We can compute an approximation to the derivative of $f(x)=x^{3}-x-1$ at $x=3$ .
[src:hindley-milner-deep/standard-ml] The Basis Library has been standardized and ships with most implementations.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/standard-ml] It provides modules for trees, arrays, and other data structures, and input/output and system interfaces.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/standard-ml] For numerical computing, a Matrix module exists (but is currently broken), https://www.cs.cmu.edu/afs/cs/project/pscico/pscico/src/matrix/README.html.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/standard-ml] For graphics, cairo-sml is an open source interface to the Cairo graphics library.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/standard-ml] For machine learning, a library for graphical models exists.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/standard-ml] All of these implementations are open-source and freely available.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/standard-ml] Most are implemented themselves in Standard ML.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/standard-ml] There are no longer any commercial implementations; Harlequin, now defunct, once produced a commercial IDE and compiler called MLWorks which passed on to Xanalys and was later open-sourced after it was acquired by Ravenbrook Limited on April 26, 2013.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/standard-ml] The IT University of Copenhagen's entire enterprise architecture is implemented in around 100,000 lines of SML, including staff records, payroll, course administration and feedback, student project management, and web-based self-service interfaces.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/standard-ml] The proof assistants HOL4, Isabelle, LEGO, and Twelf are written in Standard ML.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/standard-ml] It is also used by compiler writers and integrated circuit designers such as ARM.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/value-restriction] In programming languages with Hindley–Milner type inference and imperative features, in particular the ML programming language family, the **value restriction** means that declarations are only polymorphically generalized if they are syntactic values (also called *non-expansive*).
[src:hindley-milner-deep/value-restriction] The value restriction prevents reference cells from holding values of different types and preserves type safety.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/value-restriction] In the Hindley–Milner type system, expressions can be given multiple types through parametric polymorphism.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/value-restriction] But naively giving multiple types to references breaks type safety.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/value-restriction] The following are typing rules for references and related operators in ML-like languages.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/value-restriction] Given these, the following program unsoundly applies a function meant for integers to a Boolean value.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/value-restriction] Under the value restriction, the types of let bound expressions are only generalized if the expressions are *syntactic values*.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/value-restriction] In his paper, Wright considers the following to be syntactic values: constants, variables, ${\textstyle \lambda }$ -expressions and constructors applied to values.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/value-restriction] The function and operator applications are not considered values.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/value-restriction] In particular, applications of the ${\mathtt {ref}}$ operator are not generalized.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/value-restriction] It is safe to generalize type variables of syntactic values because their evaluation cannot cause any side-effects such as writing to a reference.
[src:hindley-milner-deep/value-restriction] The above example is rejected by the type checker under the value restriction as follows.
